          "$type": "text",
          "text": "Two separate things here, and I want to address them in order of urgency.\n\n**The lightheadedness first.**\n\nThat's not something to train around or self-treat. Lightheadedness after runs can have several causes, and some of them matter medically. Before you change your diet, your training, or start any supplement, get bloodwork done. Ask your doctor to check ferritin specifically, not just hemoglobin. Many runners, particularly female runners with high training loads, run low on ferritin while their hemoglobin looks normal. That distinction matters for how it gets treated.\n\nI can't tell you whether to take iron supplements. That's your doctor's call, based on your actual levels. Iron supplementation without a confirmed deficiency can cause harm. Please don't skip that step.\n\n**On the keto question.**\n\nWhat draws you to that approach? I ask because the reasoning matters. Fat adaptation is real physiology, but the evidence for ketogenic diets in endurance performance is mixed, and there are real tradeoffs worth understanding before you commit to anything.\n\nWhat I can tell you is that your long runs at marathon effort deplete glycogen, and that's almost certainly contributing to the energy drop you're feeling. The timing and composition of what you eat before and during those runs is squarely in coaching territory, and there's meaningful ground to cover there.\n\nI won't give you a meal plan. That's a registered dietitian's work, and given that you're training for a marathon and dealing with a potential health symptom, a sports dietitian specifically would be worth the investment.\n\n**Here's the practical next step.**\n\nTwo things to do this week. First, book an appointment with your GP and ask for ferritin, full blood count, and any other markers they think are relevant given your training load and symptoms. Second, if you want, we can talk through fueling timing for your long runs. That's something I can actually help with.\n\nWhat does your fueling look like on a typical long run right now?"
        }
      ],
